Here's a multi-form question based on the provided documentation:

Question: In TikZ, which of the following approaches would correctly create a node with a label above it and the main text below, all enclosed in a single border?

A) Use the standard label option:
   \node[text width=6em,draw,label={[above,draw]:label}] {main text};

B) Create a custom command using fit library:
   \newcommand{\mynode}[2]{%
     \node[text width=6em, outer sep=0pt] (a) {#2};
     \node[draw, above=0pt of a, outer sep=0pt] (b) {#1};
     \node[fit=(a) (b), draw, inner sep=0pt]{};
   }

C) Use the tcolorbox package:
   \newtcolorbox{mybox}[2][]{
     title=#2,
     enhanced,
     sharp corners,
     size=small,
     colback=white,
     attach boxed title to top center={yshift*=-\tcboxedtitleheight},
     text width=6em,
     halign=flush left,
     coltitle=black,
     boxed title style={colback=white, sharp corners, size=small},
     #1
   }

D) Use a custom TikZ style:
   \tikzset{
     withlabel/.style={%
       append after command={%
         \pgfextra
           \node[draw, anchor=south, outer sep=0pt] (\tikzlastnode-label) at (\tikzlastnode.north) {#1};
           \node[fit={(\tikzlastnode) (\tikzlastnode-label)}, 
           draw, inner sep=0pt]  (\tikzlastnode) {};
         \endpgfextra
       }
     }
   }

Correct Answer: D

Explanation: Option D is the correct answer because it provides a custom TikZ style that achieves the desired layout efficiently. It creates a label node above the main node, then uses the fit library to enclose both in a single border. This approach is flexible, reusable, and doesn't require additional packages.

Option A is incorrect because it places the label below the node, not above. 

Option B, while functional, is more complex and less flexible than D.

Option C uses tcolorbox, which is a separate package and may be overkill for this specific task in a TikZ environment.

